Conference Press
10845 Le Conte Avenue,
Los Angeles, California
January 2, 1937
Dear Sherwood Anderson,
Barbara Dorr, who has come to be our secretary, showed us your kind letter to her and so we are encouraged, to go ahead, and more than that, to ask to go ahead with you.
Let me explain who we are and what we have done. We are three fellows who are managing to stay in college and who met Wiliam Saroyan and then and there decied to be publishers, to publish his book, which we did - we borrowed some money, we had some, and the sum was

enough for a down payment to the printer and some extra money, so we began. The book, called Three Times Three and by Wm Sar-oyan is out. Even thru our in-experience, our ignorance, the book came out and now we are selling it and hope to have all the first thousand copie's gone soon for we are preparing the second book. It is by Gertrude Stein. We have the manuscript, her blessing, an enthusiastic illustraor who was the cartoonist for the University daily last year when I was editor and who went to New York to make his unclear. He didnt really believe the part about starving but now he doesn't

believe about or in the promise of a fotune - so he's coming back to California and we are working together. That is tow, the other two are Bill Okie and Hal Levy. Bill was feature editor last year and Hal radio editor. We are friends and also we have admired Gertrude together very long, so we are very close. Now this is it. We want to have a book of yours for our third book, for two reasons: because people know you and like you and buy you, but really

more than that, we like you. After Gertrude we like you, so we want you to follow. We want to go on publishing because there are many writers we have all read and been deeply impressed by and as long as they exist for us we will be excited and honored bo place their writing into books. It was a coincidence. The whole business, our being here now, was. Bernard Fay came to the University to lecture. Bill and unclear spoke to him. He was very nice. We took him to his hotel. Then the day after that Hal and Bill and I

went to a small college out of town where he was lecturing and heard him speak again, then we talked him again and he showed us two lectures by Miss Stein. They were wonder-ful. He was translating them into French. They had not yet been printed in English. Then we wrote Miss Stein, I had been writing to her, and she replied with yes. Will you go in with us-we would thank you more than you know. Very sincerely yours, Gilbert Harrison

Los Angeles, Calif. 
December 4, 1933
Dear Mr. Anderson; From quite a few sources I have read of your friends hip with Gertrude Stein and have been told that your writing was influenced in some degree by Miss Stein. For that reason I am writing to you. I'm really begging you for some information that I need. You see, I'm writing a University English term paper on the subject of Gertrude Stein. The dickens of it is that I can't find enough genuine estimates of Miss Stein's work, or more important still, her influence on other writers of the day. To what extent has she affected the work of you or Ernest Hemmingway? Is it that Miss Stein is just an extraordinary personality that makes her important? Or has she really something fundamental to impart thru her writings? If it is merely her personality, what is there so distinguishing about her? Is she just infatuated with her new form of writing and is losing her self in the style rather than in the subject matter? Or is Miss Stein just interested in breaking as far away from traditionalism in literature as possible? Do you believe she is really contributing something worthwhile, or is she merely creating a disturbance. Finally, and above all, have you found in your contacts with Miss Stein, a new stirring note which will radically affect the writing of the future. I will anxiously await your comments on my dilemna. Your friend, Gilbert Harrison 16250 Lucerne Blvd.

The Colonial Furniture Co. 2193-5-7-9 Ontario Street Cleveland, Ohio
May 24th, 1940
Mr. Sherwood Anderson, Trout Dale, Va.
Dear Mr. Anderson:-
Greetings from Cleveland, Ohio. I hope you had a pleasant winter and that your ambition to travel to South America for a short time was realized. In your letter to me dated October 14, 39 you sug-gested that I get in touch with you in May re autographing my books. If you are now located at Trout Dale for the summer may I have your permission to mail them to you? Of course, I would include return postage. Since writing you before I have acquired and read "Far"? and I liked it immensely. Best wishes for a pleasant summer, Sincerely yours, Ralph D. Hartman

12/13/32
My dear Sherwood Anderson: This is merely to say that I asked the publishers to send you my book Forgotten Frontiers with "cordial homage" of the author as they say here. I would not burden you to say if it reached you or not, except that so far away I am not certain that my instructions to the publishers have always been observed- I wanted you to have it since you make a part of it. And please let this letter convey my thanks to you for allowing the use of letters of yours to unclear. I meant long ago to thank you - I have read a review of your last book Which makes me eager to read it. But here in Nice it is hard to get American

publications. But I shall try. With best of wishes unclear Dudley Harvey
La Reserve
Villegrauche - unclear France
December 13, 1932
